In Faro, Portugal, a serious gaming approach was used for heritage fieldwork that used
values-based design as the driver instead of the traditional ``material-based'' approach
that focused only on physical preservation \citep{andrade2025}. The same approach is
utilized in this study as a design framework that applies a values-based design on a
gamified approach to let players assign values to virtual heritage sites. On the other
hand, a recent study utilized the Gamification Theory to bridge the gap between
technology and psychology \citep{oliveira2025}, similar to how this study also bridges
the gap between psychological theory and technical implementation through the system
architecture, gameplay and elements, and the content and its context. On another note,
the Technology Acceptance Model served as the cognitive ``bridge'' between the
technological fit and the eventual learning outcomes for a study focused around the
