\section{Statistical Treatment of Data}

In retrospect to the utilized data-gathering tool in this study, the researchers opted
to use descriptive statistics to analyze and interpret the collected data gathered from
the respondents. This analysis was done using the process of calculating the weighted
mean. Interpretation of the resulting data, on the other hand, was done using the
Likert Scale.

\textbf{Weighted Mean.} The weighted mean is calculated by multiplying each value by
its weight, summing these products, and then dividing the total by the sum of all the
weights.

\[
\text{Weighted Average} = \frac{\sum wx}{\sum w}
\]

Where: $\Sigma =$ ``sum up''; $w =$ the weight for each data point;
$x =$ the value of each data point.

\textbf{Frequency Mean.} The frequency distribution displays the number of occurrences
(frequency or $f$) of each distinct value or category within a dataset. It provides a
summary of the distribution of values or categories for interpretation and analysis of
the data.

\textbf{Percentage Distribution.} Percentage distribution is a statistical tool used
to show how a whole is divided among different categories.

\[
\text{Percentage} = \left(\frac{f}{n}\right) \times 100\%
\]

Where: $f$ represents the frequency of the value; $n$ signifies the number of
population.

\textbf{Likert Scale.} The resulting weighted mean was interpreted in the range from
numbers 1 to 5, the lowest signifying that the response strongly disagreed with the
statement while the highest strongly agreed.

