\chapter{Conclusion and Recommendations}

\section{Summary of Findings}

The research focused on the issue regarding the lack of alternative options to showcase
landmarks from the Municipality of Tinambac in a more entertaining manner. The
researchers identified and sought to address the following problems: (1) which landmarks
to incorporate in the gamified application, (2) how it will provide information about
the landmarks, (3) what design it will employ to provide entertainment on top of the
information, and (4) the level of acceptability of the gamified application.

The research used a quantitative approach to gain concrete feedback from user testing.
The gathered data was divided into 4 categories: Demographic data, Player Experience,
Knowledge and Awareness of Tinambac, and Perceived Impact and Recommendation. All
categories contributed to gaining a better understanding of the effectiveness of the
gamified approach for promoting the local tourism of the Municipality of Tinambac.

\section{Conclusions}

\textbf{Problem \#1: Which specific landmarks in Tinambac will be incorporated into
the game?} The researchers chose 4 specific landmarks from the 44 barangays of the
Municipality of Tinambac: the Municipal Hall of Tinambac (barangay Binalay), St.\
Paschal Baylon Parish Church (barangay San Pascual), Caloco beach, and Cagliliog beach.
The game incorporated each landmark in a respective manner.

\textbf{Problem \#2: What design will the gamified application employ to provide
information about landmarks in Tinambac?} The gamified application employed real-world
assets, landmark names, and cultural nuances, as well as mini-game or quest completion
prompts, to provide information about each landmark. The overall map within the gamified
application also served as a medium to disseminate information by providing a layout of
the Municipality of Tinambac with pinned locations for the incorporated landmarks.

\textbf{Problem \#3: What design will the gamified application employ to provide the
necessary entertainment on top of the essential information?} The gamified application
employed combinations of a quest system for the sequential exploration of the landmarks,
interactive mini-games within each landmark, and real-life photos with corresponding
information made possible by game interactions and the completion of mini-games.

\textbf{Problem \#4: What is the level of acceptability of the gamified application?}
The game was successful in its informational role---participants strongly agreed that
it provided clear and useful information (mean 4.3). It sparked curiosity about the
locality (mean 3.5) and increased appreciation through real-life settings (mean 3.9).
Players found the game engaging and fun (mean 3.1) and felt it effectively provided
entertainment (mean 3.3). The game's atmosphere, including sound and music (mean 3.6),
contributed positively to the player experience.

\section{Recommendations}

\textbf{Landmarks.} Using virtual reality (VR) for further enhancement of both
entertainment and immersion to the gamified approach. As well as choosing more landmarks
to provide diversity for the player and adding a layer to tour length and
interactiveness in consideration of each added landmark.

\textbf{Information Dissemination Design.} Provide other means to disseminate
information, such as using interactable signs, NPC interactions, and better exploration
opportunities for the user or player.

\textbf{Entertainment Design.} Add side activities or characters that provide
information on top of the main progression of the game. Place an option in the main
menu for manual viewing of available relevant information about the landmarks
incorporated in the game.

\textbf{Game Mechanics and Element Functionality.} The primary constraint on the
entertainment factor was the player's enjoyment of the core game mechanics, such as
puzzles and exploration, which received the weakest rating (mean 3.2). The mechanics
themselves require refinement to maximize player satisfaction.

